  1. Store the string "Hello, World!" as a variable called s.
s <- "Hello, World!"
  1. Split s programmatically into the two words Hello and World! (hint: ?strsplit).
strsplit(s, ", ")[[1]]
[1] "Hello"  "World!"
  1. Replace World with your own name (hint: ?gsub).
gsub("World", "Chris", s)
[1] "Hello, Chris!"
  1. Replace World with your own name (hint: ?substr).
substr(s, 8, 12)
[1] "World"
substr(s, 8, 12) <- "Chris"
s
[1] "Hello, Chris!"
  1. Find the string containing needle in the vector c("haystack needle", "needle") (hint: ?agrep).
# when value=TRUE, return the matching strings
agrep("needle", c("haystack needle", "haystack"), value=TRUE)
[1] "haystack needle"
# when value=FALSE, return index of the matching strings
haystack <- c("haystack needle", "haystack")
haystack[agrep("needle", haystack, value=FALSE)]
[1] "haystack needle"
  1. Find the string containing needle in the vector c("haystack needle", "needle") (hint: ?grep).
# usual wild cards
grep("*needle*", c("haystack needle", "haystack"), value=TRUE)
[1] "haystack needle"
# PERL regular expression
grep("^.*(needle).*?", c("haystack needle", "haystack"), 
     perl=TRUE, value=TRUE)
[1] "haystack needle"

if, if else

Exercises

  1. Write a plot function that takes two parameters: x, a numeric vector; and difference, a boolean. When difference is TRUE, plot the difference of x, otherwise plot x. Do this with a single if statement. Hint: ?diff.
myplot <- function(x, difference, ...){
   if (difference) x <- diff(x)
   plot(x, ...)
}

par(mfrow=c(1,2), mar=par()$mar-c(1,0,2,0), cex=0.8)

x <- rnorm(20, 100)

myplot(x, difference=FALSE, type="l")
myplot(x, difference=TRUE, type="l")

2. Write a plot function that takes two parameters: x, a numeric vector; and difference, a boolean. When difference is TRUE, plot the difference of x, otherwise plot x. Do this with an if-else.

myplot <- function(x, difference, ...){
   if (difference) plot(diff(x), ...)
   else plot(x, ...)
}

  1. Extend the app by adding a dropdown box which includes the options: normal, uniform, and exponential; and make appropriate changes such that the histogram plots data drawn from the selected distribution (hint: ?selectInput, ?rnorm, ?runif, and ?rexp).
library(shiny)

ui <- fluidPage(
  titlePanel("Statistical Distributions..."),
  sidebarLayout(
    sidebarPanel(
      selectInput("dist", "select distribution:",
                  choices=c("Normal"="rnorm", "Uniform"="runif", "Exponential"="rexp")),
      numericInput("n", "number of observations:", 
                   value=30, width = "100%"),
      actionButton("go", "Go", icon = icon("refresh"))
    ),
    mainPanel(
      plotOutput("distplot")
    )
  )
)

server <- function(input, output){
  plotdata <- reactive({
    input$go
    n <- isolate(input$n)
    dist <- isolate(input$dist)
    match.fun(dist)(n)
  })
  
  output$distplot <- renderPlot({
    hist(plotdata(), col="grey", border='white', 
         freq=FALSE, xlab="X", main="")
  })
}

shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

Shiny applications not supported in static R Markdown documents
2. If youâ€™re feeling particularly adventurous, add additional distributions, as well as other inputs required by various distributions. For example, ?rnorm defaults to the standard normal distribution, but other values of \(\mu\) and \(\sigma\) are possible other than 0 and 1; ?rt requires a degrees of freedom paramater to be present, and so on. Hint: ?uioutput.

library(shiny)

ui <- fluidPage(
  titlePanel("Statistical Distributions..."),
  sidebarLayout(
    sidebarPanel(
      selectInput("dist", "select distribution:",
                  choices=c("Normal", "Uniform", "Exponential")),
      uiOutput("distpars"),
      numericInput("n", "number of observations:", 
                   value=1000, width = "100%"),
      actionButton("go", "Go", icon = icon("refresh"))
    ),
    mainPanel(
      plotOutput("distplot")
    )
  )
)

server <- function(input, output){
  output$distpars <- renderUI({
    res <- list()
    if (input$dist == "Normal"){
      res[[1]] <- numericInput("mu", "\u03bc:", value = 0)
      res[[2]] <- numericInput("sigma", "\u03c3:", value = 1)
    }
    else if (input$dist == "Uniform"){
      res[[1]] <- numericInput("min", "min:", value = 0)
      res[[2]] <- numericInput("max", "max:", value = 1)
    }
    else if (input$dist == "Exponential"){
      res[[1]] <- numericInput("lambda", "\u03bb:", value = 1)
    }
    res
  })
  
  # a helper function.  return x if x is not null, and y otherwise.
  isnull <- function(x, y){
    if (is.null(x)) y
    else x
  }
  
  plotdata <- reactive({
    input$go
    n <- isolate(input$n)
    dist <- isolate(input$dist)
    if (dist == "Normal"){
      return(rnorm(n, isnull(isolate(input$mu), 0), isnull(isolate(input$sigma), 1)))
    }
    else if (dist == "Uniform"){
      return(runif(n, isnull(isolate(input$min), 0), isnull(isolate(input$max), 1)))
    }
    else if (dist == "Exponential"){
      return(rexp(n, isnull(isolate(input$lambda), 1)))
    }
    NULL
  })
  
  output$distplot <- renderPlot({
    if (is.null(plotdata())) return(NULL)
    hist(plotdata(), col="grey", border='white', 
         freq=FALSE, xlab="X", main="")
  })
}

shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)
